{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = Biliary pseudolithiasis | synonyms = | image = TCRM-79419-F02.jpg | width = | alt = | caption = Mass-like sludge in common bile duct (A) and the gallbladder (B) in a neonate who received ceftriaxone | pronounce = | field = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} '''Biliary pseudolithiasis''' refers to an unusual complication of [[ceftriaxone]] where the drug complexes with calcium and mimics [[gallstones]].<ref name="Kirejczyk">{{Cite journal | pmid = 1632349 | year = 1992 | author1 = Kirejczyk | first1 = W. M. | title = Disappearing "gallstones": Biliary pseudolithiasis complicating ceftriaxone therapy | journal = American Journal of Roentgenology | volume = 159 | issue = 2 | pages = 329‚Äì30 | last2 = Crowe | first2 = H. M. | last3 = MacKay | first3 = I. M. | last4 = Quintiliani | first4 = R | last5 = Cronin | first5 = E. B. | doi = 10.2214/ajr.159.2.1632349 }}</ref><ref name="Schaad">{{Cite journal | pmid = 2904533 | year = 1988 | author1 = Schaad | first1 = U. B. | title = Reversible ceftriaxone-associated biliary pseudolithiasis in children | journal = Lancet | volume = 2 | issue = 8625 | pages = 1411‚Äì3 | last2 = Wedgwood-Krucko | first2 = J | last3 = Tschaeppeler | first3 = H | doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(88)90596-x }}</ref> It is reversed when ceftriaxone administration is stopped.<ref name="Schaad"/> It was first described in 1988 by Schaad et al. as "reversible ceftriaxone-associated biliary pseudolithiasis".<ref name="Schaad"/>
