'''[[Cannabis]] in [[Cameroon]]''' is illegal; the drug is locally referred to as '''banga'''.<ref name="Duvall2014">{{cite book|author=Chris Duvall|title=Cannabis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SVU8BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT89|date=15 November 2014|publisher=Reaktion Books|isbn=978-1-78023-386-4|pages=89‚Äì}}</ref>

==Medical usage==
In Cameroon, women traditionally crushed cannabis leaves and applied them to the abdomen to relieve the pains of women in labor,<ref name="R√§tsch2001">{{cite book|author=Christian R√§tsch|title=Marijuana Medicine: A World Tour of the Healing and Visionary Powers of Cannabis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o_dKbMFRSzUC&pg=PA130|date=March 2001|publisher=Inner Traditions / Bear & Co|isbn=978-0-89281-933-1|pages=130‚Äì}}</ref> inserted cannabis into the vagina to maintain dry friction for their lover, and mixed cannabis with oil as a hair tonic to stimulate growth.<ref name="Kalunta-Crumpton2016">{{cite book|author=Anita Kalunta-Crumpton|title=Pan-African Issues in Drugs and Drug Control: An International Perspective|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WhirCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT40|date=3 March 2016|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-317-08433-4|pages=40‚Äì}}</ref>

In 2001, the BBC reported that Cameroon would legalize medicinal cannabis, but import its supply from Canada.<ref name="Booth2015">{{cite book|author=Martin Booth|title=Cannabis: A History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ecITBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA362|date=16 June 2015|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-1-250-08219-0|pages=362‚Äì}}</ref>

==Trafficking==
[[Douala Airport]] and [[Yaound√© Airport]] in Cameroon served as transit hubs for cannabis export to Europe, both locally-produced cannabis as well as product from DRC and Nigeria.<ref name="Daly1996">{{cite book|author=Paul V. Daly|title=The Supply of Illicit Drugs to the United States: The Nnicc Report|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LvbJsQgnlXwC&pg=PA63|date=July 1996|publisher=DIANE Publishing|isbn=978-0-7881-3942-0|pages=63‚Äì}}</ref>

