{{other persons| James Charlton}}
'''James I. Charlton''' is an American author, [[disability rights]] activist, and Executive Vice President of Access Living in Chicago.<ref>http://www.ucpress.edu/book.php?isbn=9780520224810#reviews</ref>

He holds that disability is [[Social model of disability|socially constructed]].<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=181TLdx1S5IC&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=James+Charlton+(activist)&source=bl&ots=A2GYRa84cC&sig=GH65MrUR28fuJeEOdzzl70kH1iw&hl=en&ei=SUu6TKvdA8WOjAf1n7CDBg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8&ved=0CDAQ6AEwBzgK#v=onepage&q=James%20Charlton%20(activist)&f=false| title=Disability and the media: prescriptions for change| author=Charles A. Riley| publisher=UPNE| year= 2005| isbn=978-1-58465-473-5 }}</ref>
He created a model of the [[disability rights movement]] that differentiates between a number of different kinds of organizations.

== Career ==
He has a graduate degree from the [[University of Chicago]]. Charlton has been Director of Programs, Executive Vice President and Acting President of Access Living since 1985. Charlton is an assistant professor in the Department of Disability and Human Development at the [[University of Illinois at Chicago]]. He is a member of the [[Chicago Transit Authority]]'s board of directors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ahs.uic.edu/ahs/php/content.php?sitename=dhd&type=7&id=138 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-10-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100622184635/http://www.ahs.uic.edu/ahs/php/content.php?sitename=dhd&type=7&id=138 |archivedate=June 22, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>

In 2000, he published the book ''Nothing about us without us: disability oppression and empowerment''.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ohqff8DBt9gC&printsec=frontcover&dq=James+Charlton+(activist)&source=bl&ots=5xSzc1MhTA&sig=X3ljJX2ojNeP4OQSDzhfbV-aWIQ&hl=en&ei=G0q6TMuxFoefOqCkxfQM&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&sqi=2&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAg#v=onepage&q&f=false| title=Nothing about us without us: disability oppression and empowerment|publisher=University of California Press| year= 2000| isbn= 978-0-520-22481-0 }}</ref>

Charlton authored the journal article ''Peripheral Everywhere'' about disabled persons as 
"double outcast".<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Charlton | first = James I. | date = | year = 2010 | month = | title = Peripheral Everywhere | journal = Journal of Literary & Cultural Disability Studies | volume = 4 | issue = 2 | pages = 195‚Äì200 | publisher = | issn = 1757-6458 | id = | url = http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/journal_of_literary_and_cultural_disability_studies/summary/v004/4.2.charlton.html | format = abstract | accessdate = 2010-10-17 | quote = | doi=10.3828/jlcds.2010.15}}</ref>

