'''Rice burner''' is a [[pejorative]], used as early as the 1960s, originally describing Japanese motorcycles,<ref>[[The Motor Cycle|''Motor Cycle'']] 17 November 1966 pp.674-675 ''You Say This. "Won't last. ...Many a rice burner will be clapped out within four or five years, but the Tiger 90 would last about 12 years. Paul Ayres, Woking, Surrey''". Accessed 4 May 2015</ref><ref>[[The Motor Cycle|''Motor Cycle'']] 1 December 1966 pp.740-742 ''You Say This. "Challenge on. I was interested to see the correspondence regarding the Triumph T90 and the Suzuki Super Six and the challenge issued...Having sold and serviced many Triumphs and Suzukis, I feel qualified to act without bias. Had Paul Ayres (17 November) the experience of both makes, such as comes the way of a dealer with 16 years in the trade, he would not refer to the finest two-fifty motorcycle yet manufactured as a rice burner. K.R. Harris, Aitchanbee Motor Cycles, Harrow Weald, Middlesex''." Accessed 4 May 2015</ref><ref>[[The Motor Cycle|''Motor Cycle'']] 22 December 1966 pp.834-835 ''You Say This. "Proof. We do not consider the Suzuki Super Six to be a rice-burner. Indeed, after it has drunk its petrol, it will have little appetite for anything else. A two-fifty which needs a gallon of petrol every 47 miles to travel at 60 mph must be the ultimate in low efficiency. P.J. Worsnop, P.  Woollven, Radcliffe-on-Trent, Nottingham''". Accessed 16 June 2015</ref> then later applied to Japanese cars, and eventually to Asian-made motorcycles and automobiles in general.<ref name=Lead/> The term most often refers to vehicles manufactured in [[East Asia]], where [[rice]] is a [[staple food]].<ref name=Breitenstein2004/><ref>{{Citation |title=You might be a rice rocket jockey if. (Pony Tales). |periodical=Mustang Monthly |volume= 25 |issue=5 |date = May 2002 |page=14 }}</ref> Variations include '''rice rocket''', referring most often to Japanese [[superbike]]s, '''rice machine''', '''rice grinder''' or simply '''ricer'''.<ref name=Lead/><ref>{{Citation |title=Driving Impression. Putting Godzilla through its paces |first=Lerato |last= Matebese |magazine=[[Business Day (South Africa)|Business Day]] |location=[[Johannesburg]], South Africa |date=19 November 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Formula Racing |first=D. J. |last=Palladino |newspaper=[[Santa Barbara Independent]] |location= Santa Barbara, California |date=9‚Äì16 April 2009 |volume=23 |issue=169 |page=119 }}</ref>

The adjectival variation '''riced out'''  describes the result of "overmodifying a [[sports compact]], usually with oversized or ill-matched exterior appointments".<ref name=Palmisano/> '''Rice boy''' is a US derogatory term for the driver or builder of an import-car hot rod.<ref name=Breitenstein2004/>
The terms may disparage cars which have been cheaply modified to present a deceptive or cosmetic appearance of high performance, without the capability.

The term is often defined as offensive or [[racist]] [[stereotyping]].<ref>{{Citation |title=Cassell's Dictionary of Slang |authorlink= Jonathon Green |first=Jonathon |last=Green |edition=2nd |publisher=Sterling Publishing Company |year=2005 |isbn= 978-0-304-36636-1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5GpLcC4a5fAC&pg=PA1189 |page=1189 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation |title=The color of words: an encyclopedic dictionary of ethnic bias in the United States |first=Philip |last=Herbst |publisher=Intercultural Press |year=1997 |isbn= 978-1-877864-97-1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UiZQH5gHuggC&pg=PA199 |page=199 }}</ref><ref name=Breitenstein2004>{{Citation |title=Ultimate Hot Rod Dictionary |first1= Jeff |last1=Breitenstein |first2=Troy |last2= Paiva |publisher=MotorBooks/MBI Publishing Company |year= 2004 |isbn= 978-0-7603-1823-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OtKWmLLiuTgC&pg=PA170 |page=170 }}</ref>  In some cases users of the term assert that it is not offensive or racist,<ref name=Pierson1998>{{Citation |title=The Perfect Vehicle: What Is It About Motorcycles |year=1998 |publisher=[[W. W. Norton & Company]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gX-yd9KpqdQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=the+perfect+vehcile&q=rice |page=166  |isbn=0-393-31809-5  |last=Pierson |first=Melissa Holbrook |authorlink=Melissa Holbrook Pierson}}</ref> or else treat the term as a humorous, mild insult rather than a racial slur.<ref>{{Citation |title=Motorcyclists Reclaim Youth With Hog-Wild Week In Florida; [7 Hartford North Final Edition]
|first=Helen |last=Ubinas |newspaper=[[The Hartford Courant]] |location=[[Hartford, Connecticut]] |date=14 March 1999 | page=A.1 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation |title=Spinning 'Rice Burners' Into Gold |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |location= New York, N.Y. |date=26 July 2004 |page= D.10 |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/26/automobiles/spinning-rice-burners-into-gold.html |accessdate=2011-05-09 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation |title=Bike Speak ; The Collected Lingo Of The Road Warrior |first=Bill |last=Heald |newspaper=[[The Hartford Courant]] |location=Hartford, Connecticut |date=15 June 2003 |page=14 }}</ref><ref name=Breitenstein2004/>

