{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}} {{Use British English|date=March 2018}} {{Infobox hospital | Name = Stamford and Rutland Hospital | Org/Group = [[North West Anglia NHS Foundation Trust]] | Image = Stamford_and_Rutland_Hospital_-_geograph.org.uk_-_285842.jpg | Caption = Stamford and Rutland Hospital | Width = | Logo = <!-- optional --> | Location = [[Stamford, Lincolnshire|Stamford]] | Region = [[Lincolnshire]] | State = [[England]] | Country = United Kingdom | Coordinates= {{coord|52.655159|-0.4718503|region:GB-LIN|display=title,inline}} | HealthCare = NHS | Type = Community | Speciality = | Emergency = No | Affiliation= | Beds = 22 | Founded = | Closed = <!-- optional --> | Website = {{URL|https://www.nwangliaft.nhs.uk}} | Wiki-Links = <!-- optional --> | map_type =Lincolnshire | map_caption=Shown in Lincolnshire }}
'''Stamford and Rutland Hospital''' is an elective care hospital in [[Stamford, Lincolnshire]] administered by [[North West Anglia NHS Foundation Trust]].
==History== [[File:Greyfriars' Gate - geograph.org.uk - 1044190.jpg|thumb|left|The medieval gate]] The hospital was built on a site previously occupied by [[Greyfriars, Stamford]] and donated by the [[Henry Cecil, 1st Marquess of Exeter|Marquess of Exeter]]. It was funded by a bequest from the will of surgeon Henry Fryer, designed by [[John Peter Gandy]] and opened in 1828.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://historicengland.org.uk/services-skills/education/educational-images/stamford-and-rutland-general-infirmary-deeping-road-stamford-8931|title=Stamford and Rutland General Infirmary, Deeping Road, Stamford, Lincolnshire|accessdate=13 October 2017|publisher=[[Historic England]]}}</ref>
Between 1876 and 1879 the hospital was expanded with the addition of three fever ward blocks, under architect [[Edward Browning]] with input from surgeon Dr William Newman. The wards incorporated a number of features such as centralised ward interiors and glazed internal walling, and were cited as an exemplar of single-block planning for small hospitals, particular by [[Henry Burdett]]. The fever wards are [[Listed building#Categories of listed_buildings|Grade II listed]] and are a testament to how voluntary hospitals dealt with nineteenth century epidemics of contagious disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cqc.org.uk/sites/default/files/new_reports/AAAA0596.pdf|title=The Fever Wards, Stanford Hospital, Lincolnshire|publisher=[[Historic England]]|author=Kathryn A Morrison|ISSN=2059-4453|year=2015}}</ref>
A substantial redevelopment of the hospital was completed in July 2017, which included new imaging facilities, including a permanent MRI scanning suite, and cancer treatment facilities.<ref name="hospital">{{cite web |url=https://www.nwangliaft.nhs.uk/our-hospitals/stamford-and-rutland-hospital/ |title=Stamford and Rutland Hospital |last= |first= |date= |website= |publisher=[[North West Anglia NHS Foundation Trust]] |access-date=14 October 2017 |quote=}}</ref>
==Services== The hospital provides a minor injuries unit, large scale outpatient services and day-case surgery, with the largest pain management centre in the region.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhs.uk/Services/hospitals/Services/DefaultView.aspx?id=1818 |title=Stamford and Rutland Hospital ‚Äì Departments and services |last= |first= |date= |website=NHS Choices |publisher=Department of Health |access-date=6 October 2017 |quote=}}</ref> It also has a medicine for the elderly ward with 22 intermediate care beds.<ref name="hospital"/> The trust's largest hospital, [[Peterborough City Hospital]], provides the majority of emergency and inpatient services in the area; the two together thus provide a comprehensive suite of services in a predominantly "hot" and "cold" split.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Candace |last1=Imison |first2=Lara |last2=Sonola |first3=Matthew |last3=Honeyman | first4=Shilpa |last4=Ross |date=25 November 2014 |title=The reconfiguration of clinical services: What is the evidence? |url=https://www.kingsfund.org.uk/publications/reconfiguration-clinical-services |location= |publisher=[[The King's Fund]] |page= |isbn=9781909029439 |author-link= }}</ref> It was rated "good" by the [[Care Quality Commission]] in May 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cqc.org.uk/location/RGN49 |title=Stamford and Rutland Hospital |last= |first= |date= |website= |publisher=[[Care Quality Commission]] |access-date=14 October 2017 |quote=}}</ref>
